<br>
My hope is that the high end guilds lose enough players that they have to accept my conditions.. which is to attend guild raids when I feel like it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is a sure-fire way not to get into a high end guild.  I can say that because I'm in an almost-hardcore raiding guild and it drives ME completely freaking nuts to see people who couldn't be bothered to log on for the &quot;learning&quot; raids show up and demand backflags.  I can only imagine that this feeling of expectation of effort from guildmates increases as you move up the foodchain.<br>
<br>
High end guilds need regular participation to advance.  The guild needs to learn together and progress together.  People who log on once or twice a week and haven't participated in the learning process are a drag on the guild.  <br>
<br>
If what you want is a once or twice a week raiding guild, then form one.  There's absolutely no shame in agreeing you're going to advance together at a pace you find comfortable.  The problem you WILL run into is that :<br>
<br>
1) 25% of your raiding force shows up any particular night, meaning that you need 54*4=216 people on the roster and you're going to struggle with class-specific feast/famine at raids.  &quot;Okay, last Coirnav we had 8 wizards and 3 chanters, tonight we have 2 wizards and 8 chanters, let's figure out how to beat this all over again&quot;.<br>
<br>
2) 25% of your raiding force shows up.  You have 55 people online, but no warriors.  Now go raid.<br>
<br>
3) You choose raid nights.  This lets you maintain a 60 person roster.  However, on any given appointed raid night, 25% of those don't show up because &quot;they don't feel like it&quot;.  So you grow to a 90 person roster.  On any given encounter, 20 miss the first flag and then 5 miss the backflag.  The more you do the encounter, the more people don't feel like doing it again and log off when it's called, because they don't &quot;feel like it&quot;.  Those who are dragging this process along with their willingness to do it again and again leave to go to a guild that moves along faster.  Welcome to the recruit more and backflag endless loop.<br>
<br>
Sorry if this sounds like a rant.  I will just say that the &quot;when I feel like it&quot; folks in high-end guilds are relying on the &quot;I'll come when you need me&quot; folks to carry them forward.  <br>
<br>
When my guild gets that desperate, I'll be moving on or retiring.  I'm also fairly sure that most of the other &quot;core&quot; people feel (or will feel) the same way when they stare that reality in the face.  It's too frustrating to spoon-feed the privileged few who only show up for the fast, sure things and the big merit and drop raids. <br>
<br>
This is why high-end guilds occasionally completely disband.  They recognize that they cannot recruit what they need going forward, and rather than step back, they free up their people to fill in the blanks in peer guilds.  They do no one a favor by watering down the roster with people with entirely different expectations in the game - they just delay the inevitable. <p><p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=365770> <center><img src="http://www.geocities.com/latuttle/harmsig2.jpg"></center> </img> </a></p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=harmonae>Harmonae</A> at: 6/10/04 4:51 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=quelinqrystalsinger>Quelin Qrystalsinger</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.smart-code.net/pictures/sigs/keys.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> Posts: 900<br> <font color=#330000>(6/10/04 5:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallbackstage.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19470.topic&index=64>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.smart-code.net/pictures/sigs/smallav.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Raiding</span><hr size=1> I don't know if bards burn out more then anyone else.  The only bard in my guild who has quit the game recently was a more off and on player anyway.  When he played consistantly he was on a lot and after a while he stops.  He has RL friends who play more casuallly so he's playing CoH.<br>
